# Module Federation

DXP uses Webpack 5 Module Federation at the shell (host) and Rsbuild's Module Federation plugin at each MFE (remote).

## Shell Config

```typescript
// webpack.config.ts
new ModuleFederationPlugin({
  name: 'shell',
  remotes: {}, // intentionally empty — loaded dynamically
  shared: {
    react: { singleton: true, eager: true, requiredVersion: '^18.0.0' },
    'react-dom': { singleton: true, eager: true, requiredVersion: '^18.0.0' },
  },
})
```

## MFE Config

```typescript
// rsbuild.config.ts
moduleFederationPlugin({
  name: 'featureFlags',
  exposes: { './App': './src/mount.tsx' },
  shared: { react: { singleton: true, requiredVersion: '^18.0.0' } },
})
```

## Dynamic Loading

The shell injects `<script src={manifest.url}>` at navigation time, then calls `__webpack_init_sharing__` and `window[scope].get('./App')` to retrieve the MFE factory.

# MFE Mount Contract

Defined in `@dxp/federation-contracts`. This is the single inter-team interface.

## TypeScript

```typescript
type MFEMountFn = (container: HTMLElement, props: MFEProps) => MFEInstance;

interface MFEInstance {
  unmount: () => void;
}

interface MFEProps {
  auth: AuthContext;
  router: RouterContext;
  theme: ThemeContext;
}
```

## Rules

- Default export only — Zod-validated by `loadRemote.ts`
- `unmount()` must clean up all event listeners, timers, and React roots
- `<MemoryRouter>` inside every MFE — shell owns the URL bar
- No global state leaks outside the MFE
- All UI via `@dxp/ui` — no custom components outside the design system

